  "summary": "Remote code execution via fetch-and-eval from attacker-controlled GitHub repo",
  "details": "Package is published as an 'Analytics injection helper' but its exported `activate()` function fetches a JavaScript payload from a hardcoded raw GitHub URL on a mutable `main` branch of a third-party personal repository named `c2-stager` and passes the response body directly to `eval()`, with errors silently swallowed. Any consumer calling `activate()` executes arbitrary remote code under the caller's Node.js process; the repository owner can change the served payload at any time without republishing this package. A sibling `track()` function and the 'analytics injection' framing serve as a cover story for the remote loader — `activate()` performs no analytics work. A source comment (`PAYLOAD REAL`) corroborates intent.",
